t 1410":"about 1410","1455":"1455","about 1405":"about 1405","1410":"1410","1504":"1504","1405":"1405","Baconsthorpe,Norfolk,England":"Baconsthorpe, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","Baconsthorpe, Norfolk, England":"Baconsthorpe, Norfolk, England","Lackham, Wiltshire, England":"Wiltshire, England","Norwich, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom":"Norwich, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","Austin Friars, Nrflk., Engl.":"Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","England":"England, United Kingdom","Of, Lackham, Wiltshire, England":"Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Banyard","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman, English:  see  Baynard  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Baynard","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): from the Middle English personal name <i>Bainard</i>, via Norman French from ancient Germanic <i>Beinhard</i>, perhaps from <i>bein-</i> ‘leg, bone’ or a supposed element <i>bagin-</i> ‘dispute’ + <i>-hard</i> ‘hard, brave’."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":2,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705197,"age":75,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Robert Banyard was born about 1380, in Wiltshire, England as the son of Philip Baynard. He married Joyce Brown about 1405, in Baconsthorpe, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. He died in 1462, in Norwich, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 83, and was buried in Norfolk, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"about 1380–1462":"umbes 1380–1462","1380–1462":"1380–1462","1383–1410":"1383–1410","1405–1504":"1405–1504","1410–Male":"1410–Surnud","1350–1415":"1350–1415","about 1380":"umbes 1380","1462":"1462","1350":"1350","1383":"1383","1382":"1382","ABT 1405":"umbes 1405","1380":"1380","1415":"1415","Abt 1410":"umbes 1410","1455":"1455","about 1405":"umbes 1405","1410":"1410","1504":"1504","1405":"1405","Baconsthorpe,Norfolk,England":"Baconsthorpe, Norfolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Baconsthorpe, Norfolk, England":"Baconsthorpe, Norfolk, Engl